{"by":"slg","id":47755315,"kids":[47755401,47755503],"parent":47753472,"text":"It&#x27;s interesting that this is explicitly for non-sports markets because I see no reason why this would be less applicable there. Sports betters have long talked about that the winning strategy is usually to bet the under (i.e. the no) on most bets.  The over (i.e. the yes) is generally a more exciting and fun outcome which causes it to attract more betters which in turns makes that side overpriced.<p>Like with this bot, I have no idea if that will still lead to actual positive returns.  This might just be a remnant from a time when these betting lines were set less intelligently.  But all things being equal, it seems logical that &quot;boring&quot; bets would have a better return in the long run than &quot;exciting&quot; bets as long as some betters are at least partially motivated by entertainment.<p>There&#x27;s probably a lot of knowledge like this that sports betters have built up over decades that could apply to these new forms of non-sports gambling.","time":1776101459,"type":"comment"}